    <note>Su(1) Qi [1490] His ancestors were Wugong jun Su(1). The ancestor who fled to Sichuan at the time of the Guangming (880) troubles had three sons. The eldest returned and became a great minister (xiang) of Tang. The second served in the Tang government. The youngest, Zhen [3756], remained in Sichuan as Tongling xian magistrate. This was Qi's great great grandfather. His great grandfather and grandfather served in the administration of the Meng(2) kings of Shu. When Shu was incorporated into the Song empire, his grandfather continued as a Song official. Qi was Yijian's [8115] son, Shunyuan's [1505], Shunqin's [7064], and Shunbin's [7065] father, and Xie's [1501], Yi's [1502], Bi's [7340] and Zhu's [3755] grandfather. He was the son-in-law of Wang(2) Dan [8153] and Han(1) Zong [657], father-in-law of Han(1) Wei [8051], and brother-in-law of Wang(2) Su [1881]. Han Wei, WJ, 30.1a-3a (wife, born Wang, who died in 1041 at age 55); XCB, 108.9a, 116.11a; LPJ, 6.6a; Su Shunqin, WJ, 14.202. CBD, 5, 4308.</note>
